\begin{abstract}
Clinical AI systems are predominantly benchmarked in English, yet
hundreds of millions of doctor--patient consultations in India occur
across languages ranging from Hindi and Bengali to Telugu, Tamil, and
Kannada. We present the first systematic evaluation of multilingual
clinical dialogue summarization across ten Indian languages, assessing
Mistral-7B and Qwen2.5-7B under zero-shot, few-shot, translation
(IndicTrans2), and LoRA fine-tuning conditions. We find that few-shot
prompting with same-language demonstrations \emph{degrades} performance
in 16 of 20 language--model pairs; translation helps Indo-Aryan but
harms Dravidian languages; and clinical Safety scores remain below
3.0/5.0 across every condition. Fine-tuning eliminates the
cross-lingual performance gap---post-SFT Dravidian F1 reaches parity
with English---while reducing macro-average hallucination from
$\sim$42\% to $\sim$10\%. We further contribute an eight-category
Clinical Error Taxonomy and a human evaluation study across Hindi,
Marathi, and Telugu.
\end{abstract}


